ration and Educational Work in Colonial Sudan, 1934–1956 -- tPart II Concluding Essays -- tChapter 12 Indigenous Agents of Colonial Rule in Africa and India: Defining the Colonial State through its Secondary Bureaucracy -- tChapter 13 Indigenous Cooperation: Foundation of Colonial Empires or New Historical Myth? -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhile the study of “indigenous intermediaries” is today the focus of some of the most interesting research in the historiography of colonialism, its roots extend back to at least the 1970s. The contributions to this volume revisit Ronald E. Robinson’s theory of collaboration in a range of historical contexts by melding it with theoretical perspectives derived from postcolonial studies and transnational history. In case studies ranging globally over the course of four centuries, these essays offer nuanced explorations of the varied, complex interactions between imperial and local actors, with particular attention to those shifting and ambivalent roles that transcend simple binaries of colonizer and colonized.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aColoniesxHistory. 0aColonizationxHistory. 0aIndigenous peoplesxPolitics and government. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Colonialism & Post-Colonialism.2bisacsh  aColonial History, History (General).1 aAusten, Ralph A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBührer, Tanja, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBührer, Tanja, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCapelão, Rosa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEichmann, Flavio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEichmann, Flavio, eeditor.4edt4http://id.l